    <!-- ============================================
         REST IN THE LAND
         ============================================ -->
    
    <div class="panel">
      <h4>Why This Matters</h4>
      <p>David's kingdom is humanity's greatest attempt at an Eden-like kingdom: Jerusalem the center of worship, the Temple God's dwelling, the land at rest. Yet even at its highest point the kingdom remains incomplete, because the king himself still bears Adam's brokenness.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Scorecard:</strong> ✓ Rest in the land · ✓ King as son · ✓ City on the mountain · ✓ Temple as Eden · ✓ River of Zion · ✓ Nations drawn · ✓ Test failed</div>

    <section class="theology-card" id="land">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🏞️</span> Rest in the Land</h2>
      <p>The conquest and settlement narratives keep returning to a single loaded word: <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">מְנוּחָה</span> (<em>menuchah</em>, rest). God gives Israel "rest on every side" (Josh 21:44; 2 Sam 7:1) — Sabbath vocabulary applied to geography. The land is presented as Eden's understudy: "a land flowing with milk and honey," watered by heaven's rain rather than human irrigation, under God's constant eye (Deut 11:10–12), where obedience means fruitfulness and God "walking among" His people (Lev 26:12). Israel in the land is meant to be the Genesis 1–2 picture at national scale: image-bearers at rest in sacred space, displaying God's order to the watching nations (Deut 4:5–8).</p>
      <p>Judges immediately shows the picture failing from the inside — "everyone did what was right in his own eyes" — and the demand for a king arises from the failure. The question the monarchy poses is Genesis 1:26 in political form: can a human being rule <em>under</em> God, as His image, rather than <em>instead of</em> Him, like the nations' kings (1 Sam 8:5, 19–20)?</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Kingship was always the plan; autonomy was the danger.</strong>
        Genesis 1 made humanity royal; Genesis 17 promised Abraham kings; Deuteronomy 17 drafted the job description (a Torah-copying king who does not multiply horses, wives, or gold). The monarchy is not a divine concession to sin — it is the image-of-God vocation institutionalized, with all the risk that entails.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE COVENANT WITH DAVID
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="david">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">👑</span> The Covenant with David</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        "I will raise up your offspring after you… and I will establish the throne of his kingdom forever. I will be his father, and he will be my son."
        <span class="reference">2 Samuel 7:12–14</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>2 Samuel 7 is the movement's hinge, and it turns on a wordplay: David proposes to build God a <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">בַּיִת</span> (<em>bayit</em>, house = temple); God answers that He will build David a <em>bayit</em> (house = dynasty). The covenant gathers the previous movements' threads into one royal line. The <em>seed</em> promised to Eve and Abraham is now narrowed to David's offspring. The great <em>name</em> promised to Abraham is promised to David (7:9). The son-of-God vocation carried by Adam and Israel ("Israel is my firstborn son," Exod 4:22) is vested in the king: "I will be his father, and he will be my son."</p>
      <p>The royal psalms unfold what the covenant is <em>for</em>, and the horizon is creation-wide. Psalm 2 installs the son on Zion with the nations as his inheritance. Psalm 72 prays for a king whose justice makes the land fruitful, whose reign extends "from sea to sea," under whom "all nations will be blessed" — Genesis 12:3 quoted as royal job description — and whose glory "fills the whole earth" (72:17, 19). Psalm 8 sits behind them all: the son of man crowned with glory, everything under his feet. The Davidic king is the creation project's designated completer.</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> Seed → nation → king. The promise keeps narrowing in order to widen: one royal line now carries the blessing meant for all nations. When the line fails, the prophets will not abandon it — they will look through it, to one son of David able to bear the weight (Isa 9, 11).</div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         THE TEMPLE
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="temple">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🏛️</span> The Temple: Eden in Cedar and Gold</h2>
      <p>Solomon's Temple completes the sequence begun in Exodus: the traveling tent becomes a fixed house, and the parallels with Genesis 1 and the Tabernacle run in a deliberate three-column series. The Tabernacle was built by Bezalel, "filled with the Spirit of God, with wisdom and understanding"; the Temple's master craftsman Hiram is introduced with the same résumé, "filled with wisdom and understanding" (1 Kgs 7:14). Creation unfolded in seven days of divine speech; the Tabernacle in seven divine speeches; the Temple is dedicated with seven petitions from Solomon and a seven-day feast (1 Kgs 8). At each dedication, glory fills the house (Exod 40:34; 1 Kgs 8:10–11).</p>
      <p>Inside, the building is a sculpted garden. The walls and doors are carved with cherubim, palm trees, and open flowers (1 Kgs 6:29–35); the pillars are crowned with pomegranates and lilies; the great basin is "the Sea," cast with gourds — the chaos waters, tamed and standing in the courtyard as furniture. To walk into the Temple was to walk, visually, back into Eden: gold, trees, guardians, and at the center, behind the veil, the presence once lost at the garden's gate. The Day of Atonement gave the imagery its liturgy — one representative human passing the cherubim into the innermost place, a ritual return to Eden on behalf of all.</p>
      <table class="pattern-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Creation (Genesis 1)</th><th>Tabernacle (Exodus 25–40)</th><th>Temple (1 Kings 6–8)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>By the Spirit of God (1:2)</td><td>Bezalel, Spirit-filled, wise (31:3)</td><td>Hiram, "filled with wisdom and understanding" (7:14)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Seven days of divine speech</td><td>Seven divine speeches</td><td>Seven petitions; seven-day feast (ch. 8)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>God rests; day made holy (2:1–3)</td><td>Glory fills the tent (40:34)</td><td>Glory fills the house (8:10–11)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Garden, trees, gold, cherubim (2:8–3:24)</td><td>Lampstand-tree, cherubim veil, gold</td><td>Carved cherubim, palms, flowers; gold overlay (6:29–35)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> Israel's sanctuaries functioned as a micro-cosmos — a scale model of heaven and earth united, where a few hundred square meters represented the whole world as God intends it. That is why the prophets can speak of the Temple's fate and creation's fate in the same breath (Jer 4:23–26; Ezek 8–11) — Movement 6's premise.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         ZION
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="zion">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">⛰️</span> Zion: The Mountain of the House</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        There is a river whose streams make glad the city of God, the holy place where the Most High dwells.
        <span class="reference">Psalm 46:4</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Around the Temple grew a theology of place. The Zion psalms (Ps 46–48; cf. Ps 36) sing of the city as the cosmic mountain — "beautiful in elevation, the joy of all the earth" (48:2) — and, strikingly, of a <em>river</em> gladdening the city of God. Jerusalem has no river; the psalmists are seeing Eden. The mountain of God's house is being portrayed as the garden-mountain of Genesis 2, the place from which life flows out to the world: "with you is the fountain of life" (36:9). Solomon's international moment — the queen of Sheba drawn by wisdom's fame, kings bringing tribute (1 Kgs 4:34; 10) — briefly stages the destination: the nations streaming toward the mountain to learn God's order (cf. Isa 2:2–4).</p>
      <p>This is the movement's high-water mark, and Scripture lets it gleam: a wise son of David at rest, a garden-temple filled with glory, the nations arriving with questions and gold. For a page or two of the story, the creation project looks nearly complete.</p>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         THE UNRAVELING
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="failure">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🥀</span> The Unraveling</h2>
      <p>The collapse begins inside the triumph, and the narrator marks it with Deuteronomy 17's checklist. Solomon multiplies horses — from Egypt, of all places; multiplies gold, until silver counts for nothing; multiplies wives, "and his wives turned his heart after other gods" (1 Kgs 10:26–11:8). The wisest of kings replays Eden's test in royal dress: seeing, desiring, taking — and building high places for rival gods on the mountain <em>east of</em> the Temple. Israel's greatest son becomes another Adam.</p>
      <p>What follows runs the familiar cycle at kingdom scale: division (one nation torn into two), generations of idolatry that Kings narrates as a long descent, prophets sent and ignored, and finally exile — first the north to Assyria, then Judah to Babylon, "removed from God's presence" (2 Kgs 17:18–23; 24:20). The theology of place turns against the people: because the Temple was creation-in-miniature, its corruption means the miniature must fall. The Bible's most devastating scene is reserved for Movement 6: the glory itself rising from the cherubim and leaving the house.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>The kingdom proved the promise and the problem simultaneously.</strong>
        Davidic rule showed what a human king ruling under God could mean for creation — fruitfulness, justice, nations drawn to wisdom. And it showed that no son of David with a Genesis 3 heart can sustain it. The monarchy's failure does not cancel Psalm 72; it prices it.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         TRAJECTORY
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="forward">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🧭</span> Trajectory: A Throne Awaiting Its King</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>What advances</h4><p>The creation project gains its royal architecture: an everlasting covenant with David's line, a city on the cosmic mountain, and a temple where Eden is carved into the walls and glory dwells behind the veil. Psalm 72's job description is now on file.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>What remains unsolved</h4><p>Every officeholder fails the Eden test. By the movement's end the kingdom is divided, the land is lost, David's heir is in a Babylonian prison — and the question has sharpened: not <em>whether</em> God's king will rule creation, but <em>who</em> can hold the office.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>What Changed?</h4><p><strong>Before:</strong> Tribes without permanent rest.<br><strong>After:</strong> A temple kingdom — pointing beyond itself.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Echoes Ahead</h4><p>The prophets' righteous Branch (Isa 11; Jer 23) · one greater than Solomon (Matt 12:42) · the temple of his body (John 2:19–21) · David's eternal throne (Luke 1:32) · the New Jerusalem (Rev 21).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="pivot-box">
        <span class="pivot-label">Where the Story Goes Next</span>
        <p>With king, city, and temple gone, the creation project appears finished. Movement 6 goes to Babylon with the exiles — where a priest named Ezekiel watches the glory leave, and then watches God begin the strangest new creation yet: not a return to what was, but the promise of something that has never existed.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="takeaway">The kingdom gives the creation project its royal form — covenant, city, and a temple carved as Eden — and proves that the form is empty until a faithful son of David fills it.</p>
    </section>

